events.description: Béla I is crowned king of Hungary.
events.html: • 1060 – Béla I is crowned king of Hungary.[1]

entities.name: Kingdom of Hungary in the Middle Ages

events.description: Mongol invasion of Rus': Kyiv, defended by Voivode Dmytro, falls to the Mongols under Batu Khan.
events.html: • 1240 – Mongol invasion of Rus': Kyiv, defended by Voivode Dmytro, falls to the Mongols under Batu Khan.[2]

events.description: After exploring the island of Cuba (which he had mistaken for Japan) for gold, Christopher Columbus lands on an island he names Hispaniola.
events.html: • 1492 – After exploring the island of Cuba (which he had mistaken for Japan) for gold, Christopher Columbus lands on an island he names Hispaniola.[3]

events.description: The city of Quito in Ecuador is founded by Spanish settlers led by Sebastián de Belalcázar.
events.html: • 1534 – The city of Quito in Ecuador is founded by Spanish settlers led by Sebastián de Belalcázar.[4]

events.description: Pride's Purge removes royalist sympathizers from Parliament so that the High Court of Justice could put the King on trial.
events.html: • 1648 – Pride's Purge removes royalist sympathizers from Parliament so that the High Court of Justice could put the King on trial.

events.description: Battle of Chamkaur: During the Mughal-Sikh Wars, an outnumbered Sikh Khalsa defeats a Mughal army.
events.html: • 1704 – Battle of Chamkaur: During the Mughal-Sikh Wars, an outnumbered Sikh Khalsa defeats a Mughal army.

entities.name: List of battles between Mughals and Sikhs

events.description: Charles Edward Stuart's army begins retreat during the second Jacobite Rising.
events.html: • 1745 – Charles Edward Stuart's army begins retreat during the second Jacobite Rising.

events.description: The U.S. Congress moves from New York City to Philadelphia.
events.html: • 1790 – The U.S. Congress moves from New York City to Philadelphia.

events.description: Five French warships attempting to escape the Royal Naval blockade of Saint-Domingue are all seized by British warships, signifying the end of the Haitian Revolution.
events.html: • 1803 – Five French warships attempting to escape the Royal Naval blockade of Saint-Domingue are all seized by British warships, signifying the end of the Haitian Revolution.[5]

events.description: Georgia ratifies the 13th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution.
events.html: • 1865 – Georgia ratifies the 13th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution.[6]

events.description: Transit of Venus, second and last of the 19th century.
events.html: • 1882 – Transit of Venus, second and last of the 19th century.[7]

events.description: The Washington Monument in Washington, D.C., is completed.
events.html: • 1884 – The Washington Monument in Washington, D.C., is completed.

events.description: London becomes the world's first city to host licensed taxicabs.
events.html: • 1897 – London becomes the world's first city to host licensed taxicabs.

events.description: Theodore Roosevelt articulated his "Corollary" to the Monroe Doctrine, stating that the U.S. would intervene in the Western Hemisphere should Latin American governments prove incapable or unstable.
events.html: • 1904 – Theodore Roosevelt articulated his "Corollary" to the Monroe Doctrine, stating that the U.S. would intervene in the Western Hemisphere should Latin American governments prove incapable or unstable.

events.description: A coal mine explosion at Monongah, West Virginia, kills 362 workers.
events.html: • 1907 – A coal mine explosion at Monongah, West Virginia, kills 362 workers.

events.description: The Nefertiti Bust is discovered.
events.html: • 1912 – The Nefertiti Bust is discovered.

events.description: World War I: The Central Powers capture Bucharest.
events.html: • 1916 – World War I: The Central Powers capture Bucharest.

events.description: Finland declares independence from the Russian Empire.
events.html: • 1917 – Finland declares independence from the Russian Empire.

events.description: Halifax Explosion: A munitions explosion near Halifax, Nova Scotia kills more than 1,900 people in the largest artificial explosion up to that time.
events.html: • 1917 – Halifax Explosion: A munitions explosion near Halifax, Nova Scotia kills more than 1,900 people in the largest artificial explosion up to that time.

events.description: World War I: USS Jacob Jones is the first American destroyer to be sunk by enemy action when it is torpedoed by German submarine SM U-53.
events.html: • 1917 – World War I: USS Jacob Jones is the first American destroyer to be sunk by enemy action when it is torpedoed by German submarine SM U-53.[8]

events.description: The Anglo-Irish Treaty is signed in London by British and Irish representatives.
events.html: • 1921 – The Anglo-Irish Treaty is signed in London by British and Irish representatives.

events.description: One year to the day after the signing of the Anglo-Irish Treaty, the Irish Free State comes into existence.
events.html: • 1922 – One year to the day after the signing of the Anglo-Irish Treaty, the Irish Free State comes into existence.

events.description: The government of Colombia sends military forces to suppress a month-long strike by United Fruit Company workers, resulting in an unknown number of deaths.
events.html: • 1928 – The government of Colombia sends military forces to suppress a month-long strike by United Fruit Company workers, resulting in an unknown number of deaths.

events.description: In United States v. One Book Called Ulysses Judge John M. Woolsey rules that James Joyce's novel Ulysses is not obscene despite coarse language and sexual content, a leading decision affirming free expression.
events.html: • 1933 – In United States v. One Book Called Ulysses Judge John M. Woolsey rules that James Joyce's novel Ulysses is not obscene despite coarse language and sexual content, a leading decision affirming free expression.

entities.name: United States v. One Book Called Ulysses

events.description: Winter War: The Red Army's advance on the Karelian Isthmus is stopped by Finns at the Mannerheim Line during the Battle of Taipale.
events.html: • 1939 – Winter War: The Red Army's advance on the Karelian Isthmus is stopped by Finns at the Mannerheim Line during the Battle of Taipale.[9]

events.description: World War II:  Camp X opens in Canada to begin training Allied secret agents for the war.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: Camp X opens in Canada to begin training Allied secret agents for the war.

events.description: A violent water polo match between Hungary and the USSR takes place during the 1956 Summer Olympics in Melbourne, against the backdrop of the Hungarian Revolution of 1956.
events.html: • 1956 – A violent water polo match between Hungary and the USSR takes place during the 1956 Summer Olympics in Melbourne, against the backdrop of the Hungarian Revolution of 1956.

events.description: Project Vanguard: A launchpad explosion of Vanguard TV3 thwarts the first United States attempt to launch a satellite into Earth orbit.
events.html: • 1957 – Project Vanguard: A launchpad explosion of Vanguard TV3 thwarts the first United States attempt to launch a satellite into Earth orbit.[10]

events.description: Adrian Kantrowitz performs the first human heart transplant in the United States.
events.html: • 1967 – Adrian Kantrowitz performs the first human heart transplant in the United States.

events.description: Altamont Free Concert: At a free concert performed by the Rolling Stones, eighteen-year old Meredith Hunter is stabbed to death by Hells Angels security guards.
events.html: • 1969 – Altamont Free Concert: At a free concert performed by the Rolling Stones, eighteen-year old Meredith Hunter is stabbed to death by Hells Angels security guards.

events.description: Pakistan severs diplomatic relations with India, initiating the Indo-Pakistani War of 1971.
events.html: • 1971 – Pakistan severs diplomatic relations with India, initiating the Indo-Pakistani War of 1971.

events.description: The Twenty-fifth Amendment: The United States House of Representatives votes 387–35 to confirm Gerald Ford as Vice President of the United States. (On November 27, the Senate confirmed him 92–3.)
events.html: • 1973 – The Twenty-fifth Amendment: The United States House of Representatives votes 387–35 to confirm Gerald Ford as Vice President of the United States. (On November 27, the Senate confirmed him 92–3.)

entities.name: Twenty-fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution
Vice President of the United States

events.description: The Troubles: Fleeing from the police, a Provisional IRA unit takes a British couple hostage in their flat on Balcombe Street, London, beginning a six-day siege.
events.html: • 1975 – The Troubles: Fleeing from the police, a Provisional IRA unit takes a British couple hostage in their flat on Balcombe Street, London, beginning a six-day siege.

events.description: South Africa grants independence to Bophuthatswana, although it is not recognized by any other country.
events.html: • 1977 – South Africa grants independence to Bophuthatswana, although it is not recognized by any other country.

events.description: Spain ratifies the Spanish Constitution of 1978 in a referendum.
events.html: • 1978 – Spain ratifies the Spanish Constitution of 1978 in a referendum.[11]

events.description: The Troubles: The Irish National Liberation Army bombs a pub frequented by British soldiers in Ballykelly, Northern Ireland, killing  eleven soldiers and six civilians.
events.html: • 1982 – The Troubles: The Irish National Liberation Army bombs a pub frequented by British soldiers in Ballykelly, Northern Ireland, killing eleven soldiers and six civilians.

events.description: The École Polytechnique massacre (or Montreal Massacre): Marc Lépine, an anti-feminist gunman, murders 14 young women at the École Polytechnique in Montreal.
events.html: • 1989 – The École Polytechnique massacre (or Montreal Massacre): Marc Lépine, an anti-feminist gunman, murders 14 young women at the École Polytechnique in Montreal.

events.description: A military jet of the Italian Air Force, abandoned by its pilot after an on-board fire, crashed into a high school near Bologna, Italy, killing 12 students and injuring 88 other people.
events.html: • 1990 – A military jet of the Italian Air Force, abandoned by its pilot after an on-board fire, crashed into a high school near Bologna, Italy, killing 12 students and injuring 88 other people.[12]

events.description: Yugoslav Wars: In Croatia, forces of the Serb-dominated Yugoslav People's Army (JNA) heaviest bombardment of Dubrovnik during a siege of seven months.
events.html: • 1991 – Yugoslav Wars: In Croatia, forces of the Serb-dominated Yugoslav People's Army (JNA) heaviest bombardment of Dubrovnik during a siege of seven months.

events.description: The Babri Masjid in Ayodhya, India, is demolished, leading to widespread riots causing the death of over 1,500 people.
events.html: • 1992 – The Babri Masjid in Ayodhya, India, is demolished, leading to widespread riots causing the death of over 1,500 people.

events.description: The United States Food and Drug Administration approves Saquinavir, the first protease inhibitor to treat HIV/AIDS. Within 2 years of its approval, annual deaths from AIDS in the United States fall from over 50,000 to approximately 18,000.
events.html: • 1995 – The United States Food and Drug Administration approves Saquinavir, the first protease inhibitor to treat HIV/AIDS. Within 2 years of its approval, annual deaths from AIDS in the United States fall from over 50,000 to approximately 18,000.[13]

events.description: in Venezuela, Hugo Chávez is victorious in presidential elections.
events.html: • 1998 – in Venezuela, Hugo Chávez is victorious in presidential elections.

events.description: A&M Records, Inc. v. Napster, Inc.: The Recording Industry Association of America sues the peer-to-peer file-sharing service Napster, alleging copyright infringement.
events.html: • 1999 – A&M Records, Inc. v. Napster, Inc.: The Recording Industry Association of America sues the peer-to-peer file-sharing service Napster, alleging copyright infringement.[14]

entities.name: A&M Records, Inc. v. Napster, Inc. (2000)

events.description: An Iranian Air Force C-130 military transport aircraft crashes into a ten-floor apartment building in a residential area of Tehran, killing all 94 on board and 12 more on the ground.
events.html: • 2005 – An Iranian Air Force C-130 military transport aircraft crashes into a ten-floor apartment building in a residential area of Tehran, killing all 94 on board and 12 more on the ground.

entities.name: Islamic Republic of Iran Air Force

events.description: NASA reveals photographs taken by Mars Global Surveyor suggesting the presence of liquid water on Mars.
events.html: • 2006 – NASA reveals photographs taken by Mars Global Surveyor suggesting the presence of liquid water on Mars.

events.description: Venezuelan parliamentary election: For the first time in 17 years, the United Socialist Party of Venezuela loses its majority in parliament.
events.html: • 2015 – Venezuelan parliamentary election: For the first time in 17 years, the United Socialist Party of Venezuela loses its majority in parliament.

events.description: Donald Trump's administration officially announces the recognition of Jerusalem as the capital of Israel.
events.html: • 2017 – Donald Trump's administration officially announces the recognition of Jerusalem as the capital of Israel.

entities.name: United States recognition of Jerusalem as Israeli capital
